00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,433
Okay.

2
00:00:00,433 --> 00:00:03,733
In this lecture, I'm going to talk about
why blocking systems

3
00:00:03,733 --> 00:00:06,733
fail specifically
in microservice architectures.

4
00:00:07,800 --> 00:00:09,633
So a lot of times

5
00:00:09,633 --> 00:00:13,066
what happens is
when I've got a microservice

6
00:00:13,066 --> 00:00:16,833
that doing work,
it can block any other requests coming in.

7
00:00:16,866 --> 00:00:19,633
This is an important
thing that we need to look for,

8
00:00:19,633 --> 00:00:21,600
and we need to be able
to handle these things.

9
00:00:21,600 --> 00:00:26,600
Where I get a latency spikes,
because maybe some underlying

10
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:27,766
processing that I have to do

11
00:00:27,766 --> 00:00:31,933
is going to take longer than the normal
for some reason, whatever the case may be.

12
00:00:32,266 --> 00:00:35,600
And I need to be able
to handle these sorts of situations.

13
00:00:35,633 --> 00:00:39,333
So we're going to talk about latency
spikes, connection

14
00:00:39,333 --> 00:00:42,333
queue growth and timeout cascade problems.

15
00:00:42,533 --> 00:00:45,600
And we're going to identify
some practical mitigation patterns.

16
00:00:45,833 --> 00:00:46,933
And then we're going to talk

17
00:00:46,933 --> 00:00:50,033
more in depth in other lectures
about some of the techniques.

18
00:00:51,066 --> 00:00:53,766
So a blocking request model

19
00:00:53,766 --> 00:00:57,633
is this when one request
comes into a microservice from another.

20
00:00:57,700 --> 00:01:02,533
So let's call it microservice a
we'll ask microservice B

21
00:01:02,533 --> 00:01:06,400
which is a worker, to do something
when it sends that request in via

22
00:01:06,433 --> 00:01:10,333
Rest interface,
yet is waiting for that response back.

23
00:01:10,333 --> 00:01:14,533
This is a typical synchronous
processing problem, right.

24
00:01:14,833 --> 00:01:18,600
So what happens is,
is if microservice B takes some time,

25
00:01:18,966 --> 00:01:21,966
then the response coming back
takes time as well.

26
00:01:22,166 --> 00:01:25,033
Now we normally see
these sorts of things happen

27
00:01:25,033 --> 00:01:27,133
when we're doing
traditional block programing.

28
00:01:27,133 --> 00:01:32,066
In one process, when we have a monolithic
process where I call a function,

29
00:01:32,833 --> 00:01:35,833
it runs through that function get
and I get the result back.

30
00:01:35,866 --> 00:01:39,733
The difference here is that that's a pure
synchronous.

31
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:41,800
The difference here in microservices

32
00:01:41,800 --> 00:01:45,600
is you've got an event loop
and things are somewhat asynchronous.

33
00:01:45,600 --> 00:01:48,600
And we're kind of forcing
some single synchronicity on there.

34
00:01:49,033 --> 00:01:52,333
So what happens is is these active workers

35
00:01:52,333 --> 00:01:54,666
because multiple things can attach to it.

36
00:01:54,666 --> 00:01:58,200
They can become very active
and overwhelmed

37
00:01:58,200 --> 00:02:02,866
on getting all of the results sent back
to all the different microservices

38
00:02:02,866 --> 00:02:04,033
that are calling them.

39
00:02:04,033 --> 00:02:06,800
And this latency on return

40
00:02:06,800 --> 00:02:09,800
ends up cascading a specific way.

41
00:02:09,800 --> 00:02:13,633
If you have like timeouts
that are not long enough and you've got,

42
00:02:13,733 --> 00:02:18,933
microservices very active
and with a lot of work going on,

43
00:02:19,366 --> 00:02:23,166
you can get those timeouts that happen
and then you can get cascading timeouts.

44
00:02:23,166 --> 00:02:25,700
If you've got microservices
calling microservices.

45
00:02:25,700 --> 00:02:28,700
So that's the sort of thing
that you have to watch out for.

46
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:30,933
So very simple.

47
00:02:30,933 --> 00:02:34,166
I've got a client out
there is calling service A.

48
00:02:34,566 --> 00:02:39,400
It's requesting something
and service A does some processing

49
00:02:39,533 --> 00:02:44,433
and then it goes and it calls service
B to say, hey, I need to do something.

50
00:02:44,633 --> 00:02:47,466
In this other service over here

51
00:02:47,466 --> 00:02:50,233
and service
B is busy doing something else.

52
00:02:50,233 --> 00:02:51,400
It could take some time.

53
00:02:51,400 --> 00:02:54,366
That's called a latency spike.

54
00:02:54,366 --> 00:02:54,666
Right.

55
00:02:54,666 --> 00:02:55,833
And it's a

56
00:02:55,833 --> 00:03:00,700
that's one of the harder things to
to deal with is latency inconsistency.

57
00:03:01,166 --> 00:03:05,933
These spikes, cause timing issues
in your own microservices.

58
00:03:05,933 --> 00:03:09,133
And if you're used to doing everything
purely synchronous

59
00:03:09,500 --> 00:03:12,000
and you want things
happen in a certain way,

60
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:14,066
there appears to be delays,
and then you don't know

61
00:03:14,066 --> 00:03:15,600
if service B actually went down.

62
00:03:15,600 --> 00:03:19,100
And you need to,
you know, send out an alert somewhere

63
00:03:19,100 --> 00:03:23,066
to somebody to, hey, try this
or do I need to do a retry?

64
00:03:23,400 --> 00:03:28,166
And you can get cascading failures,
cascading latency spikes this way.

65
00:03:28,233 --> 00:03:30,100
So things to watch out for.

66
00:03:30,100 --> 00:03:33,733
But you can see that service
now has this coupling,

67
00:03:33,733 --> 00:03:38,800
even though it's runtime
coupling with service B on, it's,

68
00:03:39,133 --> 00:03:43,133
potential behavior
based off of, latency on service B.

69
00:03:43,266 --> 00:03:46,266
So we need ways of solving that problem.

70
00:03:46,433 --> 00:03:46,700
Right.

71
00:03:46,700 --> 00:03:49,700
And there's lots of different techniques
that we're going to talk about.

72
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:53,466
One of the issues though
with these latency dependencies,

73
00:03:53,466 --> 00:03:56,466
imagine having a dozen microservices

74
00:03:57,233 --> 00:04:01,033
and almost forming a mesh
on how they communicate with each other.

75
00:04:01,333 --> 00:04:05,266
You can end up with these
really funky ways

76
00:04:05,266 --> 00:04:10,200
that, latency is popping up in different,
services at different times.

77
00:04:10,500 --> 00:04:14,433
That then just slows everything down
dramatically, right?

78
00:04:14,833 --> 00:04:17,933
And it's really important
when you're doing,

79
00:04:17,933 --> 00:04:21,333
microservice inter communication
and process communication

80
00:04:21,700 --> 00:04:26,066
that you have timeouts
that, are sufficiently long enough

81
00:04:26,300 --> 00:04:29,533
but not too long that now you're blocking
everybody else.

82
00:04:29,533 --> 00:04:32,866
Because if I'm sitting
waiting for a response from someone, then

83
00:04:32,866 --> 00:04:36,333
unblocked waiting,
and someone else could be waiting for me.

84
00:04:36,366 --> 00:04:39,300
So you gotta play around
with those timeouts a little bit

85
00:04:39,300 --> 00:04:41,566
and make sure that you retry
after those timeouts.

86
00:04:41,566 --> 00:04:45,466
And we've talked about retry timeout
feedback loops and

87
00:04:45,800 --> 00:04:49,000
and having different times in there,

88
00:04:49,333 --> 00:04:52,300
like a sleep
or wait before you try again.

89
00:04:52,300 --> 00:04:56,066
If you don't put a weight
before you try again, then you could just

90
00:04:56,066 --> 00:05:00,433
exacerbate the problem by retrying
in a very tight close feedback loop.

91
00:05:01,833 --> 00:05:02,366
Okay.

92
00:05:02,366 --> 00:05:06,066
So this is where things get
really interesting in your architecture.

93
00:05:06,066 --> 00:05:10,800
You gotta take a look and see
what, capacity

94
00:05:11,033 --> 00:05:14,533
each one of your microservices
can handle.

95
00:05:14,533 --> 00:05:16,166
And whether you need to fire up

96
00:05:16,166 --> 00:05:19,566
multiple instances
of the same microservice to handle things.

97
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:23,200
And yeah, a lot of times
it's trial and error, but

98
00:05:23,200 --> 00:05:27,500
you should be planning these things out
front, earlier than than later.

99
00:05:27,533 --> 00:05:29,100
Just keep that in mind.

100
00:05:29,100 --> 00:05:31,500
Something you should be looking at, right?

101
00:05:31,500 --> 00:05:36,133
Longer wait times means fewer
requests can be completed per second.

102
00:05:36,666 --> 00:05:41,433
So if I have a timeout, that's longer
and I could be blocking right now

103
00:05:41,633 --> 00:05:46,133
some, programing languages
like Java, for example,

104
00:05:47,200 --> 00:05:50,300
they actually have threads per request.

105
00:05:50,733 --> 00:05:54,600
And now there's some trade offs
and there's some benefits to that.

106
00:05:55,133 --> 00:05:57,000
Adding threads can increase memory

107
00:05:58,000 --> 00:05:58,700
and context

108
00:05:58,700 --> 00:06:01,700
switching overhead
inside the processor itself.

109
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:04,800
So if I'm doing if I'm doing threads

110
00:06:04,966 --> 00:06:07,966
per request, I can actually slow down
the whole machine,

111
00:06:08,900 --> 00:06:10,633
which is an interesting concept, right.

112
00:06:10,633 --> 00:06:13,933
Because now I've got so many more context
switching

113
00:06:13,933 --> 00:06:17,333
going on inside of the CPU,
which means I'm

114
00:06:17,533 --> 00:06:21,633
moving memory in and out of the CPU,
possibly virtual memory.

115
00:06:21,866 --> 00:06:24,933
It could,
it could bog the whole system down, but

116
00:06:25,633 --> 00:06:29,266
it could be much faster
than, handling things

117
00:06:29,466 --> 00:06:32,266
and less complex than handling things.

118
00:06:32,266 --> 00:06:34,533
With single threaded.

119
00:06:34,533 --> 00:06:36,233
So you've got it.

120
00:06:36,233 --> 00:06:38,466
You've got some trade offs here
that you got to deal with,

121
00:06:38,466 --> 00:06:40,966
and different languages
handle it differently.

122
00:06:40,966 --> 00:06:45,066
Good news is, is all the other languages
have the concepts.

123
00:06:45,066 --> 00:06:48,166
Some of them bake
the concepts directly into,

124
00:06:48,700 --> 00:06:51,700
the, the language itself
and the frameworks that they work in.

125
00:06:52,400 --> 00:06:52,966
Okay.

126
00:06:52,966 --> 00:06:57,633
Also remember, adding more threads
does not remove dependency latency.

127
00:06:58,666 --> 00:06:59,633
Not at all.

128
00:06:59,633 --> 00:07:01,566
You still have a dependency latency.

129
00:07:01,566 --> 00:07:05,333
It's just now I can run
multiple things in parallel, but I still

130
00:07:05,366 --> 00:07:08,366
I still have some latency,
especially in something like Java.

131
00:07:08,366 --> 00:07:10,133
When it hits garbage collect.

132
00:07:10,133 --> 00:07:12,800
Then it could slow everything down.

133
00:07:12,800 --> 00:07:15,033
All of your threads.

134
00:07:15,033 --> 00:07:18,033
So you got to watch out
for all these sorts of things.

135
00:07:18,133 --> 00:07:21,633
Okay, so here's some here's some
mitigation options that you can look at.

136
00:07:22,166 --> 00:07:25,166
You can tighten down your client timeouts.

137
00:07:25,366 --> 00:07:28,933
And you can have retries
that are bounded with timeout jitter.

138
00:07:29,033 --> 00:07:31,866
So it's not the same.

139
00:07:31,866 --> 00:07:36,566
It's not oh try again
in 5 seconds or 500 milliseconds.

140
00:07:37,433 --> 00:07:39,733
That, you know, those sorts of things

141
00:07:39,733 --> 00:07:43,100
take a look at circuit breakers
for fail fast behavior.

142
00:07:43,633 --> 00:07:44,900
These are important.

143
00:07:44,900 --> 00:07:47,833
Look at bulkheads,
which we've talked about in other,

144
00:07:47,833 --> 00:07:50,833
lectures to isolate resource pools.

145
00:07:51,266 --> 00:07:51,566
Right.

146
00:07:51,566 --> 00:07:53,533
So I don't have the effects of,

147
00:07:53,533 --> 00:07:56,533
part of my program
affecting another part of the program.

148
00:07:56,566 --> 00:08:00,133
And look for back
pressure and bounded queries.

149
00:08:00,633 --> 00:08:03,633
So instead of saying,
give me all of the orders,

150
00:08:03,933 --> 00:08:06,933
say I'm only going
to pass back 50 at a time.

151
00:08:06,933 --> 00:08:09,533
And then you can paginate,

152
00:08:09,533 --> 00:08:13,400
the rest of the rest of the, 
orders that, that you want.

153
00:08:13,633 --> 00:08:18,733
So these are ways to reduce that back
pressure or the to produce back pressure

154
00:08:18,933 --> 00:08:21,933
so that the clients aren't asking for more
than what it really needs.

155
00:08:22,133 --> 00:08:27,733
Decreasing the amount of, work that has
to happen on the microservice itself.

156
00:08:28,300 --> 00:08:31,300
So remember, there's lots of trade offs
we have to deal with.

157
00:08:31,333 --> 00:08:35,300
The blocking style is not just
simple, straightforward, right?

158
00:08:36,433 --> 00:08:38,000
It's great for simple workloads,

159
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:41,733
but debugging these things can be really,
really, difficult.

160
00:08:42,333 --> 00:08:46,366
And especially if I move to fully async

161
00:08:46,366 --> 00:08:49,400
so synchronous it's easier to debug.

162
00:08:49,400 --> 00:08:51,466
But there's trade offs here. Right.

163
00:08:51,466 --> 00:08:53,966
So we have to watch out
for those sorts of things.

164
00:08:53,966 --> 00:08:57,733
Also make sure that you're
looking at, resilience in this

165
00:08:58,533 --> 00:09:02,133
and what what
resilience plays inside this.

166
00:09:02,133 --> 00:09:05,066
If I have a microservice
that's kind of flaky and goes down a lot.

167
00:09:05,066 --> 00:09:10,533
I want to make sure that I'm not blocked
on, the client side

168
00:09:10,533 --> 00:09:14,066
or the client microservice side
that I have some options.

169
00:09:14,366 --> 00:09:17,600
And then, also,
if I have really high concurrent

170
00:09:17,600 --> 00:09:20,666
workloads, typically
I don't want these blocking things.

171
00:09:20,666 --> 00:09:26,133
So I will need to move to some async, 
technology async, techniques here.

172
00:09:27,900 --> 00:09:28,933
Okay.

173
00:09:28,933 --> 00:09:32,333
A recap blocking systems,
making RESTful calls.

174
00:09:32,700 --> 00:09:34,466
They're easier to debug.

175
00:09:34,466 --> 00:09:39,000
And they fail
through, resource saturation.

176
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:40,633
So you got to be careful there.

177
00:09:40,633 --> 00:09:43,633
They can create slow dependencies,

178
00:09:44,333 --> 00:09:46,266
between you know, queuing up

179
00:09:46,266 --> 00:09:49,600
on the microservice side and timeouts,
and you can have timeout cascades,

180
00:09:50,033 --> 00:09:53,533
but they are a whole lot easier to debug
